iginally operated from the stone store at 96 Main Street where John Hooker (H01626) also practiced law. First permanent schoolhouse built on site of Edward Hooker's (H00630) earlier 'Old Red College.' Known graduates include Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, Gloria Vanderbilt, Alice Hamilton. Sarah Porter (X01980) ran the school for 57 years until her death in 1900. History of Berlin notes it was said 'a pupil of Miss Porter's school at Farmington may be known by the way she enters a room.' Connecticut Women's Hall of Fame inductee. T01213 Eliza Talcott (1836-1911) attended as a student after being orphaned; later returned to teach there before becoming a missionary to Japan.\n[former/alt detail] Porter's School; Farmington School for Girls"}},"crossConnections":[]}